				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Agreed with arfink.  Also, you may consider ways to subtly degrade the play experience rather than crashing outright if the game detects it's running in an emulator/unauthorized reproduction--here's an article about ways this was done for a Spyro game:
<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.gamecareerguide.com/features/20011017/dodd_01.htm">http://www.gamecareerguide.com/features ... odd_01.htm</a><!-- m -->
<br />
<br />Earthbound also makes attempts to discover if its crc has been changed and adds lots of extra enemies/makes the final bossfight unwinnable if it has.  Keep in mind you don't have to have foolproof copy protection, it just needs to last a few months after your actual release really.
<br />
<br />Also, consider your audience.  If they're the type to buy a physical NES game, I'd say it's pretty likely they don't care whether a rom exists or not.  Your publisher may disagree, however.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

